  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Equation.}\n\\begin{equation}\nV_T(x)\n=\n\\lambda\n\\exp\\left(\n-\\frac{d(x,p)}{u_T}\n\\right).\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nLet $d(x,p)$ be the geodesic distance from a point $x$ to the TZP.  \nA potential localized around $p$ should be strongest at $x=p$ and decay with distance.\n\nAt the zero point:\n\n\\begin{equation}\nd(p,p)=0 .\n\\end{equation}\n\nTherefore:\n\n\\begin{equation}\nV_T(p)=\\lambda e^0=\\lambda .\n\\end{equation}\n\nTo create exponential decay away from $p$, scale distance by the Trawin base unit $u_T$:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\exp\\left(-\\frac{d(x,p)}{u_T}\\right).\n\\end{equation}\n\nMultiplying by coupling constant $\\lambda$ gives:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boxed{\nV_T(x)\n=\n\\lambda\n\\exp\\left(\n-\\frac{d(x,p)}{u_T}\n\\right).\n}\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nThe TZP potential is a localized exponential well or source centered at $p$, controlled by the coupling $\\lambda$ and decay scale $u_T$.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
  },
